The paper deals with the study of trapping sets in Tanner graphs of linear block codes, which is a topic related to information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the performance of iterative belief propagation decoders, which falls under the category of coding theory (cs.CC). The use of probabilistic and constructive methods to obtain bounds on trapping redundancy suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-categories of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and signal processing (cs.SI). Finally, the analysis of trapping sets in the context of decoding matrices suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of networking and internet architecture (cs.NI).
